Pistol Features:

The PLR-16 is a conventional, long stroke gas-piston operated semi-automatic chambered to fire the 5.56 mm NATO and .223 Remington cartridges. This pistol employs a piston and recoil assembly located over the barrel, instead of behind the grip like some AR-based pistols, along with a Johnson/Stoner breech locking system. This pistol is configured with an AR-15 type rotating bolt, but a right-side charging handle mounted to the bolt carrier is used in place of a top-mounted AR-style charging handle. The blued 9.2-inch barrel has 1:9-inch right-hand twist rifling and a muzzle cut with 1/2-28 threads to accept standard barrel attachments like flash hiders and muzzle breaks. The rear iron sight is adjustable for windage and the AR-style front sight can be adjusted for elevation. The receiver features an integrated MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny rail to accept a variety of optics.The magazine release is a square button located on the right side in front of the trigger guard. The manual safety is a cross-bolt button that blocks the trigger and sear from moving when engaged. The PLR-16 pistol arrives with a polymer 10-round magazine. The receiver also accepts most AR-15/M16-type magazines. While the firing mechanism, bolt, sights and barrel are made from steel, the upper and lower receivers are constructed of a rugged high-impact polymer. This keeps the unloaded weight of the PLR-16 down to just 3.42 pounds.

When disassembled the pieces fit inside the impact-resistant, water resistant stock. Assembly is as easy as attaching the receiver to the stock, inserting the barrel, and screwing on the nut. It comes standard with a sturdy steel barrel covered in tough ABS plastic that’s coated with Teflon™ for complete protection against corrosion. 764,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3388764,For Sale:  Perfect Grouse Gun!  (Remington 870 20 gauge),"down town, Missoula, Montana",$ 350,"Listed On: Thursday, August 14, 2014",Shotguns,Remington                                                                                ,20 Gauge                                                                                ,Pump Action                                                                                ,Shotgun,"This is the perfect grouse gun!  Its light weight (6 lbs, 2 oz), short barreled, and purpose built for chasing birds.  It’s a Remington 870 20 gauge express youth model with synthetic stock and the factory length of pull kit installed, so it’s now a full-sized stock with the full-size length-of-pull.  If you don’t want a full size stock, no problem, just remove some or all of the shims until it fits you perfectly!  Grouse like to hide thickets and dense cover, so a short gun is needed.  Because this is the youth model, it has the short 21 inch barrel that is threaded for chokes.  Rifle comes with 5 chokes: cylinder, skeet, improved cylinder, modified, and full.  This is a good selection of chokes that will meet your early and late season needs for birds, and also give you chokes that work great for home defense and hunting other game, and shooting clays.  All chokes are Carlson’s Chokes except for the modified choke, which is the Remington factory choke.  Choke wrench is included.  Grouse are hard to hit, so if you are like me, you will need a lot of practice.  Because this gun is a youth model, it has the soft squishy recoil pad, not the hard rubber pad that they put on most of their guns.  Practice all day and the combination of the soft recoil pad and the 20 gauge will not beat you up like other guns will.  Grouse are fast, so a fast fun is needed.  To help with speed, this gun has a Vang Comp extended safety button installed (the factory safety button is also included).  It’s practically impossible to get on the trigger without disengaging the safety, so you won’t miss any birds because you were fumbling with the small factory safety.  Gun also has sling studs installed so you can put a sling on it for the long walk back to your truck after a day of hunting.  As pictured, this gun only weighs 6 pounds and 2 ounces.  That’s actual measured weight, not the fake weights that most manufactures list on their websites.  This is one of the lightest shotguns that you’ll find, and anything lighter will probably cost over $1,000.  If you have hunted grouse before, you know how important a light gun is, especially after walking a couple of miles!  This gun is basically new condition.  I’ve shot 25 rounds through it as a function test and it didn’t have any problems at all.  Gun comes with 75 rounds of ammo, the original box and papers, and a BoreSnake for cleaning it.  Face to face sale in Missoula only, to a MT resident.  No trades please.  (If you noticed the small gap between the stock and the receiver, that is because I have a shim in the stock to change the angle to better fit me.  It’s very easy to remove the shim to close the gap.)"
